          "thinking": "The user wants me to implement a topological sort algorithm in TypeScript. Let me understand the specification:\n\n1. Function: Topological Sort\n2. Input: A DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph)\n3. Output: Nodes sorted so every edge u→v has u before v\n4. Also: Detect cycles\n\nI need to:\n1. Export a function that performs topological sort\n2. Detect cycles and handle them appropriately\n3. Return nodes in topologically sorted order\n\nThe spec says \"ALG-3: Topological Sort\" and mentions:\n- Sort DAG nodes so every edge u→v has u before v\n- Detect cycles\n\nI should implement:\n- A function that takes a graph representation and returns a topologically sorted array\n- Or multiple functions for different aspects\n\nCommon approaches:\n1. DFS-based (with visiting states: unvisited, visiting, visited)\n2. Kahn's algorithm (BFS-based with in-degrees)\n\nFor cycle detection, DFS with color marking (white/gray/black) is good.\n\nI need to figure out what the graph input format should be. Common options:\n- Adjacency list: Map<Node, Node[]> or Record<Node, Node[]>\n- Edge list: Array<[Node, Node]>\n- Node with edges array\n\nSince no specific format is given, I'll go with the most common: an adjacency list representation.\n\nThe function should:\n1. Return a sorted array of nodes\n2. Throw an error if a cycle is detected (since it's a \"must\" - cycles in a DAG shouldn't exist, so detecting them means invalid input)\n\nLet me implement:\n\n```typescript\nexport function topologicalSort<T>(graph: Map<T, T[]> | Record<string, string[]>): T[] {\n  // Convert to Map if Record\n  const adjList = graph instanceof Map ? graph : new Map(Object.entries(graph));\n  \n  const result: T[] = [];\n  const visited = new Set<T>();\n  const recursionStack = new Set<T>();\n  \n  const visit = (node: T): void => {\n    if (recursionStack.has(node)) {\n      throw new Error('Cycle detected in graph');\n    }\n    if (visited.has(node)) {\n      return;\n    }\n    \n    recursionStack.add(node);\n    const neighbors = adjList.get(node) || [];\n    for (const neighbor of neighbors) {\n      visit(neighbor);\n    }\n    recursionStack.delete(node);\n    \n    visited.add(node);\n    result.push(node);\n  };\n  \n  for (const node of adjList.keys()) {\n    if (!visited.has(node)) {\n      visit(node);\n    }\n  }\n  \n  return result.reverse();\n}\n```\n\nThis DFS approach uses a recursion stack to detect back edges—if I encounter a node already in the current path, there's a cycle. I process all neighbors before adding the node to results, then reverse at the end to get the correct topological order.\n\nFor the API, I need to decide what to expose. The requirements mention sorting DAG nodes and detecting cycles, so a single `topologicalSort` function that returns the ordered nodes and throws when a cycle exists seems most appropriate. The function signature would take a graph and return an array of sorted nodes.\n\nFor the graph representation, an adjacency list using `Map<T, T[]>` is the most flexible and common approach. The implementation uses DFS with a recursion stack to detect cycles—if we encounter a node already in the current path, we've found a cycle and should throw an error. Otherwise, we mark nodes as visited and build the result array in post-order.\n\nThe algorithm visits all nodes in the graph, recursively processing each neighbor before adding the current node to the result. Since DFS post-order gives us reverse topological order, we reverse the final array. This handles both the sorting requirement and validates that the graph is acyclic, throwing an Error if a cycle exists.\n\nFor the graph representation, I'll stick with Map<T, T[]> since the spec doesn't specify a particular format and this is the most straightforward approach. The implementation is solid—it correctly identifies cycles via the recursion stack and produces valid topological ordering for acyclic graphs. I'll export just the main `topologicalSort` function rather than a separate cycle detection utility, since cycle detection is already built into the sorting logic.\n\nThe algorithm handles the key edge cases properly: empty graphs return empty arrays, single nodes work correctly, disconnected components all get sorted, and nodes with no incoming or outgoing edges are processed appropriately.",
